<body>
  <div class="poster">
    <div class="section">
      <h2>Title</h2>
      <p><strong>Hybrid Machine Learning Framework for Water Quality Assessment and Clustering in the Niger Delta</strong></p>
      <p><em>Agbozu Ebingiye Nelvin, 2024</em></p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Objective</h2>
      <p>To develop a scalable ML-based framework for predicting Water Quality Index (WQI) and identifying pollution clusters across Bayelsa State using field data and machine learning models.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Data</h2>
      <p>50 geolocated water samples analyzed across 10 parameters (pH, EC, TDS, NO3, Cl, SO4, Ca, Mg, Na, Fe). WQI computed based on WHO guidelines.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Methods</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Regression:</strong> RF, XGBoost, LSTM</li>
        <li><strong>Classification:</strong> WQI class prediction</li>
        <li><strong>Clustering:</strong> K-Means for contamination grouping</li>
        <li><strong>Spatial Mapping:</strong> Heatmaps and cluster overlays</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Key Findings</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>XGBoost outperformed others (RÂ² = 0.95, AUC = 0.96)</li>
        <li>Iron, Nitrate, and EC were key drivers</li>
        <li>Majority classified as Poor or Very Poor</li>
        <li>K-Means revealed three chemical clusters</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>This hybrid ML framework provides an efficient and interpretable tool for water quality monitoring, supporting SDG 6: Clean Water and Sanitation in underserved regions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="footer">
      Poster generated using Python, TensorFlow, Scikit-learn, XGBoost, and HTML/CSS. Data collected from Bayelsa State, Nigeria.
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
